The caret package

Statistical Learning Course

21 de abril, 2021

Introduction

The caret package, short for classification and regression training, was built with several goals in mind:

  • create a unified interface for modeling and prediction (interfaces to more than 200 models),

  • to develop a set of semi-automated, reasonable approaches for optimizing the values of the tuning parameters for many of these models and

  • increase computational efficiency using parallel processing

For more details:

Website/detailed help pages: http://caret.r-forge.r-project.org

JSS Paper: http://www.jstatsoft.org/v28/i05/paper

Applied Predictive Modeling Blog: http://appliedpredictivemodeling.com/

Caret cheatsheet in Rstudio cheatsheet page: https://www.rstudio.com/resources/cheatsheets/

Example guide & create train/test sets

Sonar data from the mlbench package will be used.

  • 208 data points collected on 60 predictors (energy within a particular frequency band).

  • The goal is to predict two classes:

    • M for metal cylinder
    • R for rock

First, we the data into two groups: a training set and a test set. To do this, the createDataPartition function is used:

if(!require("caret")) install.packages("caret")
if(!require("mlbench")) install.packages("mlbench")
library("caret")
library("mlbench")
data(Sonar)
names(Sonar)

Others similar functions are: createFolds & createResample

Train function

Second, we tune a model, for example the Classification and Regression Trees based (CART) using the method = rpart1SE. This CART model replicates the same process used by the rpart function where the model complexity is determined using the one-standard error method. The train function can be used:

CART1Model <- train (Class ~ ., 
                   data=training, 
                   method="rpart1SE",
                   preProc=c("center","scale"))
CART1Model

Note:

  • preProc argument does un preprocess before to apply the model.

  • By default, the bootstrap is used to obtain the estimation error.

The trainControl function controls the type of resampling used in the train process. We will have the function use three repeats of 10-fold (by default) cross-validation.

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", repeats=3)
CART1Model3x10cv <- train (Class ~ ., 
                         data=training, 
                         method="rpart1SE",
                         trControl=ctrl,
                         preProc=c("center","scale"))

CART1Model3x10cv

TrainControl function

Additional arguments are given to trainControl:

  • summaryFunctions estimate some measure of performance:
    • defaultSummary
    • twoClassSummary
      • classProbs = TRUE option is used to computed the predicted class probabilities (which are not computed automatically).

In train function needs to indicate the custom performance measures with metric option.

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", repeats=3, classProbs=TRUE,
summaryFunction=twoClassSummary)
CART1Model3x10cv <- train (Class ~ ., 
                         data=training, 
                         method="rpart1SE", 
                         trControl=ctrl, 
                         metric="ROC", 
                         preProc=c("center","scale"))

Predict & confusionMatrix functions

To predict new samples can be used predict function.

  • type = prob : to compute class probabilities
  • type = raw : to predict the class

With confusionMatrix function will compute the confusion matrix and associated statistics for the model fit.

CART2Probs <- predict(CART2Fit3x10cv, newdata = testing, type = "prob")
CART2Classes <- predict(CART2Fit3x10cv, newdata = testing, type = "raw")
confusionMatrix(data=CART2Classes,testing$Class)

Train Process

One of the primary tools in the package is the train function which can be used to

  • evaluate, using resampling, the efect of model tuning parameters on performance

  • choose the “optimal” model across these parameters

  • estimate model performance from a training set

More formally:

Estimating Performance

To have an honest estimation of performance of the model cannot be obtained by predicting the same samples that were used to train the model. A test set and/or resampling can provide good estimates.

For regression models:

  • \(R^2\) is very popular. In many complex models, the notion of the model degrees of freedom is difficult. Unadjusted \(R^2\) can be used, but does not penalize complexity. (caret::Rsquared)

  • the root mean square error is a common metric for understanding the performance (caret::RMSE)

  • Spearman’s correlation may be applicable for models that are used to rank samples (cor(, method = "spearman"))

For classification models:

  • confusion matrix is a cross-tabulation of the observed and predicted classes.

  • overall accuracy can be used, but this may be problematic when the classes are not balanced.

  • the Kappa statistic takes into account the expected error rate:

\[ \kappa= \frac{O-E}{1-E} \]

where O is the observed accuracy and E is the expected accuracy under chance agreement.

  • For 2-class models:

    • Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curves can be used to characterize model performance.

    • Sensitivity given that a result is truly an event, what is the probability that the model will predict an event results?

    • Specificity given that a result is truly not an event, what is the probability that the model will predict a negative results?
